// The `primitive.json` sub-module: the `json` data type and its four conversions. `json` is the
// tagged mirror of a JSON document — one `data` constructor per JSON shape, closed into the union
// synonym `json` — so a program can traverse an AI's reply with ordinary `match` arms. Referenced
// from user code by the default-import qualifier: type `json.json`, constructor patterns
// `json.json_object(...)`, conversions `json.parse(...)` (or brought in bare with
// `import { type json, json_object, ... } from primitive.json`).
//
// The four conversions form two inverse pairs across the two boundaries:
//
//   - text boundary:  `parse`  (string -> json, a malformed document `panic`s)  /  `stringify`
//     (json -> string).
//   - value boundary: `encode` (any value -> json)  /  `decode` (json -> unknown).
//
// `encode` embeds a value into its wire form: a record becomes `json_object` (a `data` value keeps
// its `$constructor` entry), an array `json_array`, a `file` its `$ref` handle object, an agent its
// `$agent` reference object; a value that is ALREADY `json` passes through unchanged, so a tool list
// mixing plain fields with schemas from `get_metadata` encodes correctly. A closure cannot be
// encoded (`panic`). A secret operand taints the whole result, which then may not cross a
// user-facing boundary — the usual monotonic information-flow rule.
//
// `decode` is the checked way back into typed values: the result is `unknown`, so it is narrowed by
// `match`, or handed to `call_agent` whose delegation boundary validates it against the target's
// input schema.

@"A JSON null."
data json_null()
@"A JSON boolean."
data json_boolean(value: boolean)
@"A JSON number without a fractional part."
data json_integer(value: integer)
@"A JSON number."
data json_number(value: number)
@"A JSON string."
data json_string(value: string)
@"A JSON array."
data json_array(items: array[json])
@"A JSON object."
data json_object(entries: record[json])

// A JSON document: exactly one of the seven JSON shapes. (A `type` synonym carries no `@"..."`
// annotation; this comment is its documentation.)
type json = json_null | json_boolean | json_integer | json_number | json_string | json_array | json_object

@"Parse a JSON document from text. A malformed document raises `panic` (catchable with
`handle ... with panic(e) => ...`). A number without a fractional part parses as `json_integer`."
primitive agent parse(text: string) -> json

@"Render a `json` value as its (compact) JSON text."
primitive agent stringify(value: json) -> string

@"Embed any value into `json`: records become `json_object` (a `data` value keeps its `$constructor`
entry), arrays `json_array`, scalars their JSON shape; a `file` becomes its `$ref` handle object and
an agent its `$agent` reference object. A value that is already `json` passes through unchanged. A
closure cannot cross the JSON boundary and raises `panic`."
primitive agent encode[T](value: T) -> json

@"Read a `json` value back into a plain value (`json_object` -> record — a `$constructor` entry
re-tags the `data` value —, `json_array` -> array, scalars -> scalars). The result is `unknown`:
narrow it with `match`, or pass it to `call_agent`, whose delegation boundary validates it against
the target's input schema. A `$agent` reference cannot be turned back into a callable (`panic`)."
primitive agent decode(value: json) -> unknown
